{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1537cba-cee9-4865-a518-cdbd42869a32","content":"## What Happened\n\nC# 14 introduced **first-class span types** with implicit conversions from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes **overload resolution**: `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.\n\nExpression trees cannot represent ref struct (`ReadOnlySpan<T>`) operations, so the call fails.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`, or call `Enumerable.Contains` as a static method:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: cast to IEnumerable<int>\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option 2: explicit static call\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither approach forces the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees can represent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a685094f-c2b9-434b-92a0-878b6edd2275","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to **extension members** and how `Enumerable.Contains()` resolves for arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is about `array.Contains(num)` where `array` is `int[]`.\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, `int[].Contains(num)` resolves to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` — a static extension method call.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, the resolution might have changed — perhaps arrays now have a built-in `Contains` method or the compiler's method resolution order has shifted, which could affect how expression trees capture and translate this call.\n\